## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

**Summary: 10 tests, 9 Critical findings, 1 Medium finding.**

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called exactly once — achieving ~95% line coverage — but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if the production code is catastrophically wrong.

---

### 🔴 CRITICAL — False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic — entire class)

The test class methodically calls every public method in declaration order (`Add`, `Get`, `Update`, `Remove`, `Search`, `GetAll`, `GetProductCount`, `ApplyBulkDiscount`, `Export`, `Import`) with no meaningful assertions. This inflates coverage while verifying nothing.

#### 2. No Assertions (6 of 10 tests)

These tests have **zero assertions** — they pass even if the method silently does nothing:

| Test Method | Line | What's Missing |
|---|---|---|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17 | Never verifies the product was saved |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 31 | Never verifies the price actually changed |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 39 | Never verifies the product was deleted |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 63 | Never asserts the count value |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 68 | Never verifies prices were reduced |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 84 | Never verifies products were created |

**Fix** — example for `AddProduct_Works`:
```csharp
// BEFORE (line 17)
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// AFTER
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_ThenGetProduct_ReturnsAddedProduct()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

#### 3. Trivial `Assert.IsNotNull` Masquerading as Verification (3 tests)

`GetProduct_Works` (line 28), `SearchProducts_Works` (line 51), `GetAllProducts_Works` (line 59), and `ExportToCsv_Works` (line 81) assert only `IsNotNull`. Since `InMemoryStore` methods return `new List<>()` or non-null strings, these can never fail — they verify the return type, not the behavior.

**Fix** — example for `SearchProducts_Works`:
```csharp
// BEFORE (line 45)
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.IsNotNull(results);

// AFTER
var results = _catalog.Search("Widget");
Assert.AreEqual(1, results.Count);
Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", results[0].Sku);
```

